Background

Light pollution is a scourge on our night skies and causes a number of serious problems.
It has been linked to changes in human and animal circadian rhythms and is known to negatively impact sleep-wake cycles and overall sleep quality (Cupertino et al., 2022). It also negatively impacts wildlife and ecosystems, with bats being disproportionately affected (Cupertino et al., 2022). Haddock et al. (2019) have found that light pollution specifically at the edge of forests reduces the populations of bats.
Pothukuchi (2021) report that artificial lighting disrupts foraging of birds and that it makes them more visible to predators. They do suggest though that spiders benefit from the increased flow of moths which gather around lights.

Perez (2023) report that 83% of people across the globe live under polluted skies, and that this has severe impacts on professional and amateur astronomers as it obscures the view of the stars. The Countryside Charity (2023) found in their annual star count that only one in 20 people in the UK have access to dark skies.

Methodology

The 'Globe at Night' sky brightness monitoring network is a PPGIS dataset where stargazers can upload the results from a sky quality meter (SQM), which is an instrument to measure the brightness of the night sky.

Figures 2:1 and 2:2 show the sample points from this dataset in the UK and the UAE, which have been interpolated to produce national maps of dark skies.
Figure 2:1: UAE sample points Figure 2:2: UK sample points

A higher SQM reading indicates a darker sky.

The assumptions underpinning spatial interpolation were tested, and the results show that the data is suitable to be used for interpolation:

  • The data is largely normally distributed, if slightly positively skewed (Figure 2:3), and the QQ plots (Figure 2:4) show that the data generally fits the normal line with few outliers.
  • There is definite positive spatial autocorrelation, as shown by the positive Moran's I values in table 2:1.
  • Interpolation doesn't work fantastically over very large distances where the results are strongly clustered, which is why the UK and Dubai were chosen over the United States. Both these countries satisfy the assumptions on clustering.
  • There are no significant global trends on this scale.

The exploratory interpolation tool in ArcGIS Pro was then used to automatically determine the most accurate method of interpolation (figure 2:2) For Dubai, this was Ordinary Kriging. For the UK it was Empirical Bayesian Kriging.

Figure 2:7: Motorways in the Scottish Borders (OS Maps, 2025)

In the UK, the darkest skies are, unsurprisingly, found in areas away from large cities in places such as Northumberland National Park and the mountainous terrain of central Wales. As such, this could serve as a useful proxy for population density. Some of the darkest skies are found along the south coast on Bodmin Moor and around Hastings.

One of the biggest anomalies is around Glasgow, where there is a very wide strip of very poor quality night sky which stretches from the west coast of Scotland all the way to Dundee. This could potentially be linked to the high density of brightly lit motorways in this region. Figure 1:x shows how this strip almost exactly lines up with the M8 motorway.

The UAE has fewer anomalies than the UK, probably because the UAE has fewer major cities and it a more centralised country, The location of Dubai is immediately obvious. The UK and the UAE are however, broadly similar with near identical skew and medians.

Limitations

There are a few limitations to this methodology

  1. There are general limitations of PPGIS, including uncertainty about the accuracy of the data.
  2. There is patchy coverage of recent data; there are enough points to interpolate, but some of the data is as old as 2006 (see Figure 2:8). The old data points have been included though, as the accuracy will likely suffer more from having fewer points to interpolate than it would do from having old data. It is an assumption of this report that the data will not have changed significantly.
